article.headline: Oregon 55, Washington State 52
article.story: PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Everyone knows Oregon freshman Bryce Taylor is a good shooter, but now he is showing everyone that he's also a good listener. Taylor, responding to coach Ernie Kent's recent demands that he play more aggressively, buried his first six 3-point shots and scored a season-high 26 points to lead the Ducks past Washington State 55-52 Saturday afternoon. "He was just unreal," Kent said. "He kept us afloat. He was unstoppable." Washington State coach Dick Bennett also praised Taylor, saying, "He strikes me as a very special player." Oregon improved to 11-3 overall and 3-2 in the Pac-10 with the victory, which was its seventh consecutive win over Washington State. Thomas Kelati led Washington State (8-7, 3-3 Pac-10) with 15 points, but missed two 3-pointers in the final second -- the first shot was blocked out of bounds -- under strong defensive pressure from Jordan Kent, the son of Oregon's coach. "Jordan made a fabulous block and then made a second great defensive play," the proud father said. The Ducks trailed most of the game, including 26-24 at the half. Oregon's season scoring leader Aaron Brooks, who scored his only five points of the game in the second half, drove the lane and drew a foul from Kelati on a three-point play that pushed Oregon ahead 53-52 with 41.7 seconds to go. Maarty Leunen's two free throws with 6.6 seconds left completed the scoring. Washington State's Josh Akognon had missed the front end of a 1-and-1 free-throw opportunity with 24.9 seconds left, and Brooks raced to save the ball from going out of bounds when teammate Ian Crosswhite mistakenly bounced the ball toward an official. "Aged me 10 years," Kent joked. Taylor's 26 points -- double his season average -- ranks third in Oregon history for a freshman. On Thursday, he scored 16 points in Oregon's loss at No. 14 Washington after Kent pulled him aside for a pep talk earlier in the day. "He said, 'Bryce, I think you're doing OK, but I think you can do better," Taylor said. Taylor made 10-of-14 shots Saturday, including 6-of-8 from 3-point range. Often taking advantage of screens set to free him from Kelati, he scored 16 of Oregon's 24 points in the first half. "We weren't knocking down shots. Bryce bailed us out," Brooks said. Washington State's Derrick Low and Oregon's Malik Hairston, two of the five freshman starters in the game, both scored 10 points. Washington State's Jeff Varem, who had been averaging 17 points in conference play, was limited to five shots by Oregon's 2-3 zone defense. He scored all nine of his points in the first half. "We struggle against a zone because we don't have an inside presence," Bennett said. "Jeff is wonderful, but he needs a little bit of room to get started, and it's hard to get room against a zone." The 55-point total was a season low for Oregon.
